21:11.760 --> 21:13.797
You know, I mean, it's temporary.

21:13.880 --> 21:16.031
So we're okay. Phew!
(CHUCKLING)

21:18.120 --> 21:19.395
Up you come.

21:19.840 --> 21:21.115
(GROANING)

21:22.520 --> 21:24.034
Ah, a nice little sleep.

21:28.600 --> 21:30.159
CHANELLE: How many are you putting in?

21:30.240 --> 21:32.357
He'll have a bridge of four teeth.

21:32.440 --> 21:36.878
It's like having your permanent courtesy car
when your car goes into repair or service.

21:36.960 --> 21:39.555
He needs a courtesy set of teeth
for everything.

21:39.800 --> 21:41.871
And that's why, you know,
we're not prepared

21:41.960 --> 21:45.636
to put the implants in
and put new teeth in straight away,

21:45.720 --> 21:47.598
because you have to be careful with that.

21:47.720 --> 21:51.634
- So when he retires, then, we can...
- We need to get on with this.

21:51.760 --> 21:55.595
That's the idea. So you tell me
as and when that's gonna be...

21:55.680 --> 21:58.639
- That's the million-dollar question.
- DENTIST: Absolutely!

21:58.760 --> 22:01.673
- I'm not going to make you answer.
- We need to get on with this...

22:03.000 --> 22:05.515
We need to get going.

22:06.520 --> 22:08.671
- MCCOY: Right, we're ready to go.
- (CHUCKLES) Okay.

22:08.760 --> 22:11.355
- Super. Thank you so much.
- Just give me a smile there.

22:12.360 --> 22:14.352
Okay, we'll keep them
nice and white for you.

22:15.040 --> 22:17.760
ROBERTS: <i>Most people would tell you
they think he's made from something else,</i>

22:17.840 --> 22:23.438
<i>because I'd say 60, 70% of jockeys
would have stopped by now on what he's had.</i>

22:24.800 --> 22:28.999
<i>I mean, you know, every time they go
to ride, it could be their last ride.</i>

22:30.040 --> 22:32.157
<i>I sit and watch the race in here and</i>

22:32.240 --> 22:34.596
<i>whether it's one of my jockeys
or someone else's jockeys,</i>

22:34.680 --> 22:37.275
<i>as soon as a horse falls and you think
a jockey's had a bad fall,</i>

22:37.360 --> 22:41.559
<i>it just makes you</i> (INHALES)
<i>sit back and wince a bit,</i>

22:41.640 --> 22:43.757
<i>because you just don't know,</i>

22:43.840 --> 22:47.356
<i>you are, really, every time you ride,
that could be your last one.</i>

22:48.480 --> 22:51.632
<i>There are no guarantees.
It is a high-risk sport, I think.</i>

23:01.360 --> 23:02.999
(INDISTINCT SPORTS COMMENTARY)

23:04.760 --> 23:05.876
COMMENTATOR:
<i>Nip and tuck between these two</i>

23:05.960 --> 23:07.280
<i>as they come to the next flight.</i>

23:07.360 --> 23:09.113
<i>AP McCoy out in the front
with the racing...</i>

23:09.200 --> 23:10.680
<i>Oh, my goodness, he's fallen!</i>

23:10.760 --> 23:13.116
<i>AP McCoy takes a fall
and then the oncoming horse</i>

23:13.200 --> 23:15.317
<i>appears to step on AP at the same time.</i>

23:15.400 --> 23:18.313
<i>That looked nasty.
AP gingerly getting to his feet.</i>

23:23.560 --> 23:26.359
And you get no threes or fours...

23:26.440 --> 23:28.477
- You only got ones or twos.
- Mmm-hmm.

23:28.560 --> 23:31.632
So we need to get rid of the twos
and get all ones.

23:31.720 --> 23:34.440
- And then we'll be away, won't we?
- Mmm-hmm.

23:34.520 --> 23:36.557
- What? Do you think you'll be able to do that?
- Hmm.

23:36.680 --> 23:39.479
Evie, are you having breakfast?

23:46.920 --> 23:48.718
(SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

23:51.600 --> 23:53.000
(GROANING)

24:08.600 --> 24:10.193
I'm sore, you know.

24:10.280 --> 24:13.717
And then I rode a horse in the next race,
because I thought I would win.

24:13.800 --> 24:15.280
And, um...

24:16.560 --> 24:20.349
Luckily I did win,
and then I gave up the rest of my rides,

24:20.440 --> 24:22.591
and I didn't ride yesterday, either, so...

24:24.160 --> 24:25.833
Like, I knew it was
obviously around my chest,

24:25.920 --> 24:27.991
around my lungs area and that,

24:28.080 --> 24:32.996
but I've punctured my lungs twice
in the last two years,

24:33.680 --> 24:37.196
so I kinda know the feeling of what it's
like whenever they're punctured or not.

24:38.280 --> 24:41.193
Because your breath doesn't come back
when you puncture your lung.

24:41.280 --> 24:42.680
So it was kind of...

24:42.760 --> 24:45.594
My breath wasn't great
but it did gradually come back.

24:46.360 --> 24:47.714
But, um...

24:49.720 --> 24:51.359
- It got...
- (CHANELLE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

24:51.440 --> 24:54.000
There's a guy there.
Hard to get up there. Please.

24:56.400 --> 24:58.960
CHANELLE: Right, here.
My husband will help you.

24:59.040 --> 25:00.440
- Hi, Dave, you all right?
- Just put it on speaker.

25:01.520 --> 25:04.991
Um, good, yeah. Have you many rides
on Sunday, out of matter of interest?

25:06.520 --> 25:08.239
(DAVE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

25:08.960 --> 25:10.360
I might only ride a few of them
on Sunday then,

25:10.440 --> 25:12.113
and see how I am. And suddenly if you think

25:12.200 --> 25:13.839
any of us have got a chance,
then I'll ride it you know.

25:15.000 --> 25:17.515
All right, thanks Dave. Cheers.
Bye, bye, bye.

25:19.200 --> 25:20.475
Tell him you're not riding on Sunday.

25:21.360 --> 25:23.033
I am riding on Sunday.

25:23.120 --> 25:26.397
It's just badly bruised,
it's very sore, but it's grand.

25:28.120 --> 25:30.555
It's getting better, I
can lift my hand up now.

25:32.960 --> 25:36.032
COMMENTATOR: <i>The 19-times
champion aboard On The Record</i>

25:36.120 --> 25:38.430
<i>moves along side Roll on Ruby.</i>

25:40.680 --> 25:42.831
<i>Now McCoy has to shake up On The Record,</i>

25:42.920 --> 25:45.196
<i>and Bangkok Pete and Wayne Kavanagh</i>

25:45.280 --> 25:48.398
<i>alongside, moving on
down towards the second last.</i>

25:48.480 --> 25:52.156
<i>On the Record, galvanized by AP,
trying to see off</i>

25:52.240 --> 25:54.516
<i>the attentions of Bangkok Pete.</i>

25:54.600 --> 25:56.273
<i>Bangkok Pete just ahead.</i>

25:56.360 --> 25:58.636
<i>On the Record though, a much cleaner leap.</i>

25:58.720 --> 26:02.794
<i>And now presented with the advantage,
McCoy driving away.</i>

26:02.880 --> 26:04.917
<i>Bangkok Pete, On The Record,</i>

26:05.000 --> 26:08.710
back for more on the near
side, McCoy pulls it out the fire,

26:08.800 --> 26:12.237
and On The Record,
for the man who makes breaking records

26:12.320 --> 26:14.471
<i>look commonplace has got up to score.</i>

26:14.560 --> 26:17.678
<i>And a personal milestone is almost reached.</i>

26:18.440 --> 26:22.116
<i>AP McCoy, the champ has
equalled the number of winners,</i>

26:22.200 --> 26:24.999
<i>trained by his former boss, Martin Pipe.</i>

26:25.080 --> 26:26.878
MIKE: <i>Martin, hello there.
How are you?</i>

26:26.960 --> 26:28.440
MARTIN: <i>Hello, Mike. Very well. Thank you.</i>

26:28.520 --> 26:31.718
MIKE: <i>I bet you can't believe that he's
closing down on your record, can you?</i>

26:32.080 --> 26:35.391
<i>No, it's a challenge we've had
between us for sometime</i>

26:35.480 --> 26:38.439
<i>and he's getting so, so close.</i>

26:39.200 --> 26:40.395
<i>It really is incredible.</i>

26:40.680 --> 26:44.390
<i>To ride so many winners and still keep
going. And riding better than ever.</i>

26:46.200 --> 26:47.793
COMMENTATOR: <i>Kirby's Glen
at the rear of the field.</i>

26:47.880 --> 26:49.314
<i>So, Tony McCoy disputing third place,</i>

26:49.560 --> 26:53.236
<i>seeking to surpass Martin Pipe's
record of career wins</i>

26:53.320 --> 26:55.391
<i>which he equalled today at Uttoxeter.</i>

26:55.480 --> 26:59.030
<i>At the moment, Old Pals Act
is still right in the thick of things.</i>

26:59.120 --> 27:00.998
<i>As indeed is virtually every
single runner here,</i>

27:01.080 --> 27:02.480
<i>as Klinsman leads the turn,</i>

27:02.560 --> 27:04.995
<i>just about a circuit under
their belts. And for the first time,</i>

27:05.080 --> 27:07.720
<i>Andrew Thornton giving the impression
he just wants to press on slightly,</i>

27:07.800 --> 27:09.678
<i>but he hasn't shaken off the pursuers.</i>

27:22.680 --> 27:25.639
RACE COMMENTATOR: <i>Klinsman by
a length as he approaches the next...</i>

27:26.240 --> 27:28.436
<i>Again they're all over, in fact Kirbys Glen</i>

27:28.520 --> 27:30.591
<i>just beginning to struggle
slightly, just like</i>

27:30.680 --> 27:34.117
<i>so many we've seen. Tony McCoy
improving on a horse that so far</i>

27:34.200 --> 27:37.557
<i>hasn't really warmed to his jumping but
between the fences is travelling up well.</i>

27:37.640 --> 27:39.279
<i>Old Pals Act, then King of Dubai...</i>

27:39.400 --> 27:41.551
(COMMENTARY CONTINUES INDISTINCT)

27:41.640 --> 27:43.359
MCCOY: <i>I might have won more races
than anyone else,</i>

27:43.440 --> 27:44.874
<i>but I've lost a lot more
than everyone else too,</i>

27:44.960 --> 27:49.716
<i>so I might have the
record for the most wins,</i>

27:49.800 --> 27:51.792
<i>but I've got the records for the
most losses as well.</i>

27:53.360 --> 27:56.398
<i>I've got the record, for probably who's
fallen off the most as well.</i>

27:58.960 --> 28:02.590
<i>Because you can win
the biggest horse races in the country,</i>

28:03.520 --> 28:05.830
<i>and then next year you can be
in the back of an ambulance.</i>

28:05.920 --> 28:08.913
<i>So, you can go from a really huge high</i>

28:09.000 --> 28:11.720
<i>to a very sad low very quickly.</i>

28:14.360 --> 28:15.840
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

28:21.720 --> 28:25.191
COMMENTATOR: <i>Klinsman hasn't been left...</i>

28:25.440 --> 28:28.512
<i>And it's Klinsman! No record
this time for Tony McCoy.</i>

28:28.600 --> 28:30.910
<i>But Klinsman moves Andrew Thornton
another closer</i>

28:31.000 --> 28:33.117
<i>to his personal milestone of a thousand.</i>

28:35.440 --> 28:37.318
<i>Old Pals Act in second place...</i>

28:37.400 --> 28:38.720
(COMMENTATOR CONTINUES INDISTINCT)

28:39.040 --> 28:40.040
(ENGINE STARTING)

28:49.680 --> 28:51.353
MCCOY: It feels a bit sore
right down the middle.

28:51.920 --> 28:53.479
- THERAPIST: Okay.
- So it does.

28:55.560 --> 28:59.315
But obviously as I said to you,
about going to the garage,

28:59.600 --> 29:00.954
if you were a mechanic,

29:01.040 --> 29:03.396
the mechanic will fix you
and you'll be better whenever you leave...

29:04.480 --> 29:06.836
That's how I pretty much I...

29:06.920 --> 29:10.038
How I want to feel whenever you leave,
I'm supposed to feel better.

29:10.120 --> 29:12.760
THERAPIST:
I've told you my theory on this as well.

29:12.840 --> 29:14.991
Mechanics don't work
with old bangers, do they?

29:16.280 --> 29:17.760
(AP SIGHS)

29:19.320 --> 29:21.152
Have you coloured your hair?

29:21.240 --> 29:22.640
Have I what?

29:23.240 --> 29:24.720
There's less grey in it today.

29:25.280 --> 29:26.680
(LAUGHS)

29:29.440 --> 29:31.033
Fucking hilarious, you are.

29:32.160 --> 29:34.391
I've got to have a good sense of humour
to work with you.

29:36.560 --> 29:38.517
- MCCOY: Yeah, see, there it's quite sore.
- Yeah.

29:39.520 --> 29:41.716
- That's the...
- That's the old fracture.

29:41.960 --> 29:44.634
So is that... Is that just...

29:44.720 --> 29:46.837
'Cause I don't think
that's been sore before.

29:46.920 --> 29:49.389
But you were sore last time
when I saw you last week.

29:49.480 --> 29:51.915
I'm just going to work through,
trying to release any tension

29:52.000 --> 29:53.753
through your soft tissue here.

30:00.160 --> 30:03.471
It'd be so much easier if they didn't
stand on you whenever they fall.

30:04.000 --> 30:05.229
Don't fall off.

30:05.880 --> 30:07.200
Thanks.

30:07.760 --> 30:09.319
(INDISTINCT COMMENTARY)

30:25.480 --> 30:26.914
(SHOUTING)

30:28.120 --> 30:30.680
Right, don't get me, guys.
I'm with the kids, okay?

30:30.760 --> 30:32.160
We're all against AP.

30:32.240 --> 30:34.197
MCCOY: That little terrorist. Yous got me!

30:35.000 --> 30:38.152
I got a fall, and when I fell, I fell away
but the horse come behind me.

