32:37.560 --> 32:39.153
<i>Just that, I think...</i>

32:39.240 --> 32:42.199
<i>I don't what I've been doing
the last 20 years 'cause</i>

32:42.280 --> 32:43.873
<i>this summer's been better than any of them.</i>

32:43.960 --> 32:46.873
For some reason, I've
been luckier this time.

32:46.960 --> 32:48.440
Well, I know why I've been luckier
this time around,

32:48.520 --> 32:49.840
I'm riding for a lot of people.

32:49.920 --> 32:54.312
Um, Jason Maguire, unfortunately for him,
got a really bad injury...

32:54.400 --> 32:57.518
Um, the Monday before Cheltenham
and he hasn't ridden since.

32:57.600 --> 33:01.435
You know, he was... Well, he was
practically dead, to be honest.

33:01.920 --> 33:06.437
Um, you know, I think he was resuscitated
at one point on the way to hospital

33:06.520 --> 33:09.194
and he hasn't ridden since then.

33:09.280 --> 33:13.035
And Jason is first jockey
to Donald McCain who is, um...

33:13.720 --> 33:17.680
You know, a very powerful stable and
I've been lucky enough to ride

33:17.760 --> 33:21.117
the best part of 25 winners for him
that I wouldn't have ridden.

33:21.760 --> 33:25.754
Um, I've also ridden, I think 12 winners
for Kim Bailey,

33:25.840 --> 33:27.957
which Jason would have ridden as well, so,

33:28.040 --> 33:31.750
you know, I've probably ridden the best part
of 40 winners that Jason might've ridden.

33:31.960 --> 33:34.316
MCCOY: <i>So it is possible
to ride 300 winners.</i>

33:35.360 --> 33:38.797
<i>Three hundred winners means
you've got to ride a winner every day</i>

33:38.880 --> 33:41.349
<i>other than 65 days in the year.</i>

33:41.440 --> 33:44.319
<i>There's only 65 days in the year
that you cannot ride a winner.</i>

33:48.440 --> 33:49.590
CHANELLE: <i>Hi, you're smelling good.</i>

33:50.400 --> 33:52.790
Well, hey, how it's going? Hey, guys.

33:53.840 --> 33:55.479
Good. Cheers, lads. See you in a bit.

33:58.040 --> 33:59.269
Um...

34:00.840 --> 34:04.151
It'll be getting worse now
as he's getting better, you know.

34:04.240 --> 34:07.153
- Because you'd be feeling like he's nearly...
- Like he can get back, you know?

34:07.240 --> 34:09.708
That's the worst of it but, look...

34:10.639 --> 34:12.871
He's a lucky boy, Chanelle,
he was bloody dead.

34:14.719 --> 34:17.076
And there was something else he was
quite lucky with as well.

34:22.520 --> 34:26.196
Do you know, just when you just say that,
it actually nearly puts me off my food.

34:26.280 --> 34:27.554
MCCOY: Hmm?

34:27.639 --> 34:32.032
In the space of ten minutes we are talking
about two jockeys being resuscitated.

34:34.159 --> 34:35.958
(CLEARS THROAT)
It's just the way it is, Chanelle.

34:37.280 --> 34:38.760
I don't know, honey, I mean,

34:38.840 --> 34:42.550
I know you're absolutely flying this year
and I know it's hard,

34:42.639 --> 34:44.518
but I think...

34:44.600 --> 34:49.277
I think, this year is a good year, honey,
to call it a day.

34:49.360 --> 34:52.273
- What?
- (CHUCKLES) You heard me.

34:56.000 --> 34:58.435
- This year is a good year to call it a day?
- Yeah.

35:00.000 --> 35:01.673
CHANELLE: I've too many bones in my fish.

35:03.640 --> 35:07.839
Why on Earth would any year
be a good year to call it a day?

35:11.640 --> 35:13.359
What's meant to be is meant to be.

35:13.440 --> 35:15.750
I know, but you can't, you know,
I mean, you can't...

35:16.840 --> 35:20.277
Yes, I agree to that, but unfortunately,
with some things...

35:22.160 --> 35:24.629
You know, some things you have to
make a decision,

35:24.720 --> 35:28.031
- you can't until the decision is made for you.
- I know that.

35:34.280 --> 35:35.873
I've had enough of that conversation now.

35:35.960 --> 35:38.429
Okay, I know, but I'm just...
All I'm saying to you is

35:38.520 --> 35:41.957
if the season doesn't go
the way you planned, right?

35:42.040 --> 35:44.111
God forbid you get an injury... God forbid.

35:44.920 --> 35:47.196
How did I let you
get on this conversation during dinner?

35:47.280 --> 35:48.839
Well, I just...

35:48.920 --> 35:51.276
Cause I...
It's hard to talk to you about it at home

35:51.360 --> 35:54.239
because you're watching
Sky Sports and your Sky Plus,

35:54.320 --> 35:56.551
and this and that and you're not...

35:56.640 --> 35:58.199
Like...

35:58.960 --> 36:00.599
- Yeah.
- You're not engaged.

36:02.840 --> 36:04.274
- What happens now?
- Okay, so the other scenario is...

36:04.360 --> 36:06.238
So suddenly my life goes from being...

36:08.440 --> 36:11.672
Doing everything I wanted to do
for last 20 odd years,

36:11.760 --> 36:15.310
to waking up and thinking,
"Mmm, what happens today then?"

36:16.840 --> 36:20.390
Well, listen, they'll be a few lunch boxes
for you to pack, honey.

36:20.480 --> 36:21.755
(CHUCKLES)

36:21.840 --> 36:24.480
They'll be a few bins for you to take out.

36:26.240 --> 36:27.240
Seriously.

36:32.920 --> 36:33.956
(PHONE BEEPS)

36:34.040 --> 36:37.078
ROBERTS: Hi, Rebecca. Just to say, um,
AP can ride both horses tomorrow.

36:37.160 --> 36:39.800
How about it in the 1.40 at Chepstow?

36:40.680 --> 36:43.070
AP is available if you want him. No?

36:45.680 --> 36:47.160
Okay, no problem.

36:47.840 --> 36:50.833
<i>The only time you'll realise
what he's achieved</i>

36:50.920 --> 36:52.400
<i>is when he retires.</i>

36:54.560 --> 36:56.711
<i>We've never spoke about
it, apart from once,</i>

36:56.800 --> 36:59.395
<i>and the conversation
lasted about five seconds.</i>

37:00.360 --> 37:02.192
<i>It's not on the agenda at the moment.</i>

37:03.440 --> 37:06.080
<i>No, I hope he goes on as long as possible.</i>

37:07.840 --> 37:10.674
<i>What he's achieved,
I don't think will ever be matched.</i>

37:11.560 --> 37:14.439
<i>I... I honestly don't think in my lifetime</i>

37:14.520 --> 37:17.354
<i>someone will get to 4,000 winners again.</i>

37:18.920 --> 37:21.913
To be able to stay in
one piece for 20 years

37:22.000 --> 37:25.880
and to ride 200 winners
a year in that time,

37:25.960 --> 37:27.599
I can't see that happening.

37:31.320 --> 37:34.279
(INDISTINCT COMMENTARY)

37:34.360 --> 37:37.432
He's just had a fall, sorry to interrupt,
he's just fell.

37:42.400 --> 37:43.993
That did not look very good.

37:54.240 --> 37:57.631
If in doubt,
just to put his foot in the ditch, yeah.

38:14.480 --> 38:15.960
NURSE: I'm leaving you with the results?

38:16.040 --> 38:19.317
Um, I think someone was gonna
send them on to my doctor, I think.

38:19.400 --> 38:20.595
NURSE: Okay.

38:23.720 --> 38:27.600
CHANELLE: <i>Hi.</i>
MCCOY: <i>Hey, I went in to see the doctor.</i>

38:27.680 --> 38:30.275
<i>And he said I was fine, Chanelle.</i>

38:30.360 --> 38:32.033
<i>He said I'm perfect, you know.</i>

38:33.320 --> 38:35.630
CHANELLE: <i>Did he see your broken rib?</i>

38:36.400 --> 38:40.440
MCCOY: <i>He said he'd seen in my x-rays there
was lots of old broken ribs and, yeah,</i>

38:40.520 --> 38:42.716
<i>everything else looked perfect, he said.</i>

38:47.440 --> 38:50.433
<i>But it wasn't like you convincing him,
"I'm fine to ride."</i>

38:50.520 --> 38:52.477
<i>- Did he say you can ride.</i>
- MCCOY: <i>Chanelle...</i>

38:52.560 --> 38:56.315
<i>But did you ask him if you have a fall,
and, you know, could it...</i>

38:56.400 --> 38:59.677
MCCOY: <i>I did, Chanelle. He said...</i>

38:59.760 --> 39:01.353
CHANELLE: <i>Could your problem get bigger?</i>

39:01.440 --> 39:03.238
He said,
"There's a bigger risk of you on a horse

39:03.320 --> 39:05.437
"than there is your lung being a problem."

39:05.520 --> 39:10.515
<i>Okay, so if you have a fall tomorrow,
and you get any impact around your lung,</i>

39:10.600 --> 39:14.560
<i>then it shouldn't be dangerous.</i>

39:14.640 --> 39:16.916
It's no different than normal, you know...

39:17.000 --> 39:19.720
<i>He said there is no more risk
than there is normal risk.</i>

39:21.480 --> 39:23.312
DOCTOR: <i>How do you feel today?</i>
MCCOY: <i>Perfect.</i>

39:25.840 --> 39:27.479
DOCTOR: Why do you say perfect?

39:27.560 --> 39:29.916
MCCOY: If you'd asked me
on Friday what I feel like,

39:30.000 --> 39:32.310
I'd have been delighted
if I felt the way I do today...

39:33.440 --> 39:35.193
CHANELLE: <i>Okay, so you're
going to ride then tomorrow.</i>

39:35.280 --> 39:36.953
I am, I am.

39:38.600 --> 39:40.239
I'll see you when I get home.

39:40.320 --> 39:42.198
<i>- Okay, bye-bye.</i>
- Bye-bye.

39:51.640 --> 39:53.393
(INDISTINCT RACING COMMENTARY)

39:59.680 --> 40:02.559
COMMENTATOR: <i>It is Goodwood Mirage
in the hands of Tony McCoy driven out here.</i>

40:02.680 --> 40:06.390
<i>About a length or so ahead of Lightning Rod
who tries to fight back and does so.</i>

40:06.480 --> 40:09.279
<i>Goodwood Mirage just...
Goodwood Mirage, the far side.</i>

40:09.360 --> 40:11.829
<i>We'll call that one hundred
and fiftieth for AP this season.</i>

40:11.920 --> 40:15.038
<i>Lightning Rod in the centre,
to the outside is Tidal Wave...</i>

40:27.400 --> 40:30.279
(HEAVY BREATHING)

40:37.040 --> 40:38.952
DOCTOR: What we can do today is just, um,

40:39.040 --> 40:41.794
help the healing of the injury
with the injection.

40:41.880 --> 40:43.837
- You happy with that? Yeah? Okay.
- MCCOY: Yeah.

40:49.280 --> 40:51.431
DOCTOR: Okay,
so just spin that around like that.

40:51.520 --> 40:52.590
- You're all right there?
- MCCOY: Yeah.

40:52.680 --> 40:54.319
DOCTOR: Got to give quarter of an hour.

41:10.800 --> 41:12.154
- All done.
- Thank you.

41:12.240 --> 41:13.515
- Feel okay?
- Yeah.

41:13.600 --> 41:15.080
- Sure? Take it easy.
- Absolutely.

41:24.920 --> 41:26.274
(APPLAUSE)

41:30.120 --> 41:32.032
CHANELLE: I think he is better looking.

41:32.120 --> 41:33.440
What do you think, Evie?

41:36.120 --> 41:37.998
- Can you sit down?
- Yeah, yeah.

41:38.080 --> 41:40.834
No, I'm all right now. I'm all right...
I was sore yesterday.

41:40.920 --> 41:42.991
I've been very badly
wounded as well, you know.

41:43.080 --> 41:46.198
I was on the ground
and I could not get a breath.

41:46.280 --> 41:48.476
If he gave me a shot of morphine,
I'll show you the way then.

41:50.760 --> 41:52.956
And he said to me...
He stood in the kitchen and he said to me,

41:53.080 --> 41:55.231
"I'm going to retire at
the end of the year."

41:55.320 --> 41:57.596
And I said to him, "What?"

41:57.680 --> 42:00.639
And he said to me, "Yeah I'm going
to retire at the end of the year."

42:01.280 --> 42:04.034
And then about five minutes later
he sat down and says to me,

42:04.120 --> 42:05.679
"I'm only joking, Chanelle,
but you know what,

42:05.760 --> 42:08.878
"I did that because I wanted to see
what it felt like, me saying,

42:08.960 --> 42:10.314
'I'm going to retire."'

42:10.920 --> 42:13.674
And I said to him,
"Well, how did it sit with you?"

42:14.360 --> 42:17.717
And he said to me, "I just felt
like getting sick after I said it."

42:18.760 --> 42:20.353
Do you know, it was...

42:20.440 --> 42:21.920
Bye darling.

42:22.040 --> 42:23.713
- Four years.
- (LAUGHS)

42:23.800 --> 42:26.634
Four years, it has to be like... 250...

42:26.720 --> 42:28.473
Even if I ride 250 winners
in the next three years,

42:28.560 --> 42:29.789
that three years is enough.

42:29.880 --> 42:32.236
No, okay, anyway.

42:32.320 --> 42:35.996
- Three years is enough, right?
- But I think we're making baby steps, Ms Pipe.

42:36.120 --> 42:37.873
MS PIPE: Yeah, he only said it
to know what it feels like.

42:37.960 --> 42:40.714
CHANELLE: I wanted to hear myself saying,
I wanted to see what it felt like.

42:40.800 --> 42:42.871
- It didn't work.
- It didn't work. No. Okay.

42:43.000 --> 42:44.229
You didn't like that.

42:44.520 --> 42:46.637
And now I think I'm
invincible, so I'm all right.

42:58.040 --> 43:00.316
(INDISTINCT COMMENTARY
IN THE BACKGROUND)

43:25.040 --> 43:26.793
COMMENTATOR:
<i>Pitches, and unseats McCoy.</i>

43:26.880 --> 43:28.439
<i>Gives him a tumbling fall.</i>

43:57.520 --> 43:59.876
COMMENTATOR:
<i>And If In Doubt gave the rider no chance.</i>

44:01.160 --> 44:02.719
<i>Tony McCoy had no chance.</i>

44:20.680 --> 44:22.717
- Hi, Chappers, how are you?
<i>- I'm all right.</i>

44:22.800 --> 44:24.792
<i>I'm well. I'm a lot better than you.
How are you?</i>

44:24.880 --> 44:28.271
MCCOY: <i>Erm, I'm not sure whether I'm
worse physically or mentally,</i>

44:28.360 --> 44:31.353
<i>but, um, neither's probably great
at the moment, to be honest.</i>

44:31.840 --> 44:35.436
But I suppose,
probably for the last month I've been...

44:35.520 --> 44:37.637
Um, I've been suffering a little bit,

44:37.720 --> 44:39.677
and obviously because that I, you know...

44:39.760 --> 44:41.911
Obviously, I was wanting to ride
300 winners this season,

44:42.000 --> 44:45.357
I couldn't afford to have any time off,
and, um...

44:45.440 --> 44:48.114
Because of that, you know,
you try and keep going,

44:48.240 --> 44:50.755
you try and keep going through it and then
I had another fall on Tuesday.

44:50.840 --> 44:53.196
And I've been trying to get through it

44:53.280 --> 44:55.590
and sadly I'm going to have to sit out
for a couple of weeks.

44:55.680 --> 44:59.230
Which is not good mentally or physically,
but probably worse mentally at the moment.

45:01.280 --> 45:03.351
<i>I wouldn't have carried on what I did,</i>

45:03.440 --> 45:05.113
<i>only that I thought
I was going to ride 300 winners,</i>

45:05.680 --> 45:06.955
<i>so that's gone now.</i>

45:07.920 --> 45:09.195
<i>So, that's the end of that.</i>

45:10.920 --> 45:13.560
- Have you packed my bags?
- This... Okay...

45:13.640 --> 45:14.960
Remind me why I'm bringing you again?

45:15.040 --> 45:16.076
(CHANELLE GIGGLES)

45:16.160 --> 45:18.436
CHANELLE: I'm on suicide watch.
That's why.

45:20.360 --> 45:23.353
I'm not packing for you
by the way, just so you know.

45:23.440 --> 45:25.591
So what are the advantages
of being married to you?

45:25.680 --> 45:27.876
Well, I've given you two
nice kids, haven't I?

45:29.240 --> 45:30.435
Seriously.

45:33.120 --> 45:34.395
All right. Come on.

45:34.480 --> 45:35.994
If you want me to pack your bag, I will.

45:41.160 --> 45:43.311
I don't actually want to go on holidays.

45:43.400 --> 45:45.073
- Do you not?
- No.

45:45.800 --> 45:49.077
God, Ant, talking about, like...

45:49.160 --> 45:51.755
Wrecking my buzz, why do you not
want to go on holidays?

45:53.440 --> 45:56.797
Well, do I need to state the obvious?

45:57.600 --> 45:58.795
Because the only reason
you're going on holiday

45:58.880 --> 46:00.712
- is because you're not riding.
- Yeah.

46:00.960 --> 46:01.960
CHANELLE: Yeah.

46:02.680 --> 46:05.559
But you've a week now
to recharge your battery,

46:05.640 --> 46:09.111
get your collarbone in the sun, vitamin D.

46:09.440 --> 46:13.559
And can you just try and accept
you have an injury

46:15.800 --> 46:17.280
and you are... You know what I mean,

46:17.360 --> 46:19.591
that you're not just going
to be completely...

46:19.680 --> 46:21.831
Actually, can I just ask,

46:21.920 --> 46:24.640
you're not going to be completely
frying my head for the next week.

46:24.720 --> 46:26.279
Because that's what'll happen.

46:27.480 --> 46:29.836
And you know what, honey,
it's not all about you.

46:30.480 --> 46:31.480
Since when?

46:32.800 --> 46:33.800
It's not...

46:34.760 --> 46:37.832
Because I have a job, I work

46:38.600 --> 46:41.399
and it's nice for me
to get away and de-stress as well

46:41.480 --> 46:42.914
from, on holidays,

46:43.680 --> 46:44.680
you know?

46:45.120 --> 46:47.396
I wonder if I just ate the whole packet,
would it help me.

46:48.400 --> 46:52.633
No, Ant, because your liver
can only absorb so much...

46:54.400 --> 46:56.153
You know, so much of the tablet.

46:57.400 --> 46:59.960
(SIGHS) Right.
How many nights are we there for?

47:00.680 --> 47:03.070
Sunday, Monday, Tuesday,
Wednesday, Thursday...

47:04.680 --> 47:06.000
Friday. Five nights.

47:07.600 --> 47:08.920
You're starting to do my head in now

47:09.000 --> 47:10.480
and we haven't even got outside the door.

47:11.120 --> 47:13.715
I mean, I'm quite glad now
that we're settled into the house

47:13.800 --> 47:15.996
that you have stopped
telling me to pinch myself

47:16.080 --> 47:17.753
that I'm so lucky to be married to you.

47:18.880 --> 47:21.031
You've been injured
every time we've been there.

47:21.120 --> 47:23.715
Even when we went on our honeymoon,
you were in a sling.

47:23.800 --> 47:25.234
(MOBILE PHONE RINGS)

47:26.520 --> 47:27.520
Well...

47:28.320 --> 47:29.993
Yeah, me collarbones.

47:30.080 --> 47:32.549
Um, I dislocated it and it's broke as well

47:33.720 --> 47:34.915
so I was kind of getting through it

47:35.000 --> 47:36.878
then I got a fall on
Tuesday and I kind of...

47:37.920 --> 47:39.070
That kind of ended it.

47:40.120 --> 47:42.271
So we're going away in the morning,
myself and Chanelle.

47:43.880 --> 47:45.280
Going to Barbados for a week.

47:46.760 --> 47:49.480
I'm only going, really,
because the sun might help it.

47:49.560 --> 47:51.517
<i>For the first four or five days
when I was off,</i>

47:51.600 --> 47:53.319
<i>I always wanted to bang
my shoulder off the walls,</i>

47:53.400 --> 47:55.676
<i>you know what I mean,
'cause I was kind of thinking that</i>

47:55.760 --> 47:58.434
<i>it deserves to be punished
for doing this to me.</i>

47:59.800 --> 48:02.713
Some part has to take the blame,
why should it be me?

48:04.280 --> 48:05.634
I'm not the one that's being weak,

48:06.440 --> 48:08.591
part of my body is being weak, not me.

48:09.480 --> 48:11.153
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

48:14.960 --> 48:16.633
MCCOY: That was me.
MAN: That was you?

48:16.720 --> 48:17.720
MCCOY: Yeah.

48:19.480 --> 48:20.994
(CROWD CHEERING AND WHISTLING)

48:25.120 --> 48:27.589
MCCOY: That was me as well. Yeah.

48:40.360 --> 48:42.636
SPORTS COMMENTATOR: <i>I've not
seen him since he went off to Barbados,</i>

48:42.720 --> 48:46.316
<i>he looks healthier now. He looks as though
the rest has done him good.</i>

48:46.720 --> 48:48.074
SPORTS COMMENTATOR 2:
<i>He has been severely beaten up</i>

48:48.160 --> 48:50.959
<i>over the past few weeks,
he hasn't ridden since November the fifth.</i>

48:51.880 --> 48:54.270
SPORTS COMMENTATOR: <i>Yeah, I mean,
he's had a nightmare...</i>

48:54.360 --> 48:56.158
<i>The sort of run he couldn't afford.</i>

48:56.240 --> 48:59.756
SPORTS COMMENTATOR 2: <i>He could
hardly walk into the room.</i>

48:59.840 --> 49:01.991
SPORTS COMMENTATOR:
<i>White as a sheet, haggard.</i>

49:04.240 --> 49:06.277
SPORTS COMMENTATOR 2: <i>For example,
Muhammad Ali had a great chin,</i>

49:06.360 --> 49:10.320
<i>no one ever knocked him out.
AP has got an amazing pain threshold.</i>

49:10.400 --> 49:11.675
SPORTS COMMENTATOR:
<i>And he's proud of it.</i>

49:12.280 --> 49:16.069
<i>This was one of his last great frontiers,
the 300 winners in a season.</i>

49:18.360 --> 49:20.033
MAN: <i>AP McCoy!</i>

49:20.120 --> 49:21.918
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

49:32.600 --> 49:38.949
<i>Another incredible time, it seems
you are going from strength to strength.</i>

49:39.760 --> 49:42.070
<i>Yeah, it's going well but, you know,
though as I say,</i>

49:42.160 --> 49:44.277
<i>just hopefully keeping it going,
that's the thing, isn't it,</i>

49:44.360 --> 49:48.149
<i>you know, making your job as hard
as possible because you've been struggling</i>

49:48.240 --> 49:49.720
<i>pretty much all night, you know,
with your interviews,</i>

49:49.800 --> 49:51.951
<i>that say "I'm not sure whether you'll be
back or not, will you?"</i>

49:52.040 --> 49:55.750
<i>No, no, you're absolutely fine, you can
keep talking as long as you want.</i>

49:55.840 --> 49:57.593
<i>I'm off, best of luck, thanks.</i>

49:57.680 --> 49:58.909
<i>When are you going to hang your coat up?</i>

49:59.640 --> 50:02.599
<i>Ah, look, as you said, you're only as good
as your luck. Well, I was going to say,</i>

50:02.680 --> 50:04.160
<i>you're only as good as your last
winner. In your case,</i>

50:04.240 --> 50:08.280
<i>- you're only as good as your last haircut.</i>
- (LAUGHING)

50:08.360 --> 50:10.272
<i>And in your case, I don't know</i>

50:10.360 --> 50:11.794
<i>what the fuck you're still doing here.</i>

50:12.960 --> 50:15.111
<i>Ladies and gentlemen, AP McCoy!</i>

50:32.480 --> 50:36.474
SPORTS COMMENTATOR: <i>Alan, what do
you think in his mind, is the benchmark</i>

50:36.560 --> 50:39.439
<i>when he says, "I've done
it, that's enough."</i>

50:41.040 --> 50:44.351
<i>Is it 20 titles, is it 5000,</i>

50:45.920 --> 50:49.197
<i>is it to win another Gold Cup,
is it to win another National?</i>

50:49.720 --> 50:52.076
Oh, you want to try one, yeah?
I don't think that'll be very good.

50:52.160 --> 50:54.117
SPORTS COMMENTATOR 2: <i>He obviously
wants to win the big races,</i>

50:54.200 --> 50:55.350
<i>but the fact is he's won them all.</i>

50:58.400 --> 51:01.234
<i>I think he constantly wants to
do things he hasn't done before</i>

51:02.080 --> 51:05.232
<i>and that's why the 300 was
such a big thing for him.</i>

51:05.600 --> 51:09.753
<i>And that's why I still, in my mind,
wonder how that's going to affect him,</i>

51:09.840 --> 51:11.433
<i>the failure to do it.</i>

51:13.160 --> 51:18.110
<i>It could mean, that he wants to go on
even longer. Failure in his mind.</i>

51:21.680 --> 51:23.637
MCCOY: So Chanelle just said,
"Can you come for dinner?"

51:23.720 --> 51:28.920
ROBERTS: Yep, just said... Yeah, you know,
we've been trying to get together,

51:29.000 --> 51:32.277
obviously but it's, uh... She said,
"Can come this week?"

51:33.120 --> 51:34.120
Uh,

51:35.280 --> 51:38.671
and it was all arranged by Chanelle,
nothing to do with AP. And...

51:42.400 --> 51:45.916
So I don't honestly know, is the answer.

51:47.920 --> 51:50.674
May just be dinner. I don't know.

51:58.320 --> 51:59.959
MCCOY: <i>Well, I got injured after that.</i>

52:00.040 --> 52:05.877
And then I was gone riding for three days
after that, but that was brain dead.

52:05.960 --> 52:08.191
But... (LAUGHING)

52:08.880 --> 52:12.794
- I actually...
- Should we tell him our secret now?

52:12.880 --> 52:17.113
I actually said "I still think one of
your best rides you'll ever give a horse

52:17.200 --> 52:18.714
"was Good Mirage at Weatherby."

52:18.800 --> 52:21.190
- Oh yeah.
- Because you were riding that with one hand,

52:21.280 --> 52:22.316
- weren't you...
- I know.

52:22.400 --> 52:23.800
- And proudly...
- And it pulled like mad,

52:23.880 --> 52:26.315
it was a horrible horse
to ride in that sense.

52:26.400 --> 52:30.553
And the whole thing was is that
you were so stubborn about it,

52:30.800 --> 52:34.396
you know, that it was like well, you know,
"I'm not listening to my collarbone,

52:34.480 --> 52:38.269
"I'm not, so what if it's shattered,
it's hanging off, my lung is punctured,

52:38.360 --> 52:40.920
"my ribs are broken. I
will continue riding."

52:41.480 --> 52:46.316
MCCOY: That really mentally fucked up
my head. Broke my heart, that did,

52:46.880 --> 52:49.440
thinking that I actually was going
to ride 300 winners, and then,

52:49.520 --> 52:50.920
I'm not going to ride 300 winners.

52:51.400 --> 52:52.754
Oh, it was just...

52:53.320 --> 52:54.993
The thought of it makes me want to cry.

52:55.560 --> 52:59.031
And... And then I was, you know,

52:59.120 --> 53:03.478
and then, I was thinking, you know,
I should retire at the end of the year.

53:06.040 --> 53:08.680
I should retire at the end of the year
and then I'm thinking,

53:09.520 --> 53:11.000
I don't even know when I should retire.

53:11.080 --> 53:14.232
I don't know whether I should announce
I'm going to retire at the end of the year?

53:14.320 --> 53:15.320
I don't.

53:16.280 --> 53:18.511
You know, should I retire when
I ride my two hundredth winner,

53:18.960 --> 53:24.354
or just retire in a week's time or
six weeks' time or two months' time?

53:24.720 --> 53:28.270
ROBERTS: Personally for me,
I would like to go out on a winner.

53:28.440 --> 53:32.673
- What have you got now one, nine...
- 182, was it?

53:32.760 --> 53:37.596
ROBERTS: 184, I think... So say you said
that on the two hundredth you announce it...

53:37.680 --> 53:38.680
CHANELLE: Mmm-hmm.

53:38.760 --> 53:42.231
ROBERTS: So on a normal run of things,
16 winners.

53:42.640 --> 53:44.836
Announcing it on

53:45.600 --> 53:48.354
February 14th, 15th, around that time.

53:48.840 --> 53:50.718
CHANELLE: Be the same as the
4,000 winners, you were on tour

53:50.800 --> 53:51.800
for like three or four days.

53:51.880 --> 53:55.715
Like I am, just because
it's the right thing to do,

53:55.960 --> 53:59.317
I will hopefully retire on one of
JonJo's horses that JP owns.

53:59.400 --> 54:01.232
ROBERTS: Yeah. So it should be on
the green and gold colours.

54:01.320 --> 54:03.516
MCCOY: It's got to be one of JonJo's in
the green and gold colours.

54:03.600 --> 54:04.795
ROBERTS: Yeah, exactly.

54:05.040 --> 54:06.040
I'm not shocked.

54:08.040 --> 54:12.193
I'm upset because it's the end
of a great story if you want to

54:12.280 --> 54:15.512
look it like that, but then
in the cold light of day,

54:15.920 --> 54:19.072
what we've achieved, as I say, I...
Whether you agree with me or not,

54:19.160 --> 54:22.756
no one will... No one will do that,
it's not possible.

54:22.840 --> 54:23.840
MCCOY: Mmm.

54:23.920 --> 54:28.278
ROBERTS: For someone to ride 2000 winners,
they've got to ride for 20 years,

54:28.560 --> 54:30.552
and ride 100 winners a year, for 20 years.

54:30.880 --> 54:32.599
That's half of what you've got.

54:34.080 --> 54:35.080
I think.

54:35.160 --> 54:36.958
So that's the plan. I think 200 is good.

54:37.040 --> 54:39.350
ROBERTS: Yeah. No, I think 200 is right.
Definitely.

54:39.880 --> 54:41.314
CHANELLE: I think it's a good decision.

54:41.400 --> 54:43.551
- ROBERTS: To me it feels right.
- Yeah, I think it feels right too.

54:43.640 --> 54:45.359
Let's just agree upon, I'll say. (LAUGHS)

54:45.440 --> 54:48.831
I... I think it feels right,
I actually think it feels right.

54:48.920 --> 54:51.196
I actually feel happy now that
I've spoke about it.

54:51.960 --> 54:54.634
I think once you get to that 200,
you announce it,

54:54.720 --> 54:55.949
and then the...

54:56.120 --> 54:59.670
I think it'll take a lot of pressure,
takes it... It's there, it's done.

54:59.760 --> 55:01.479
- Yeah.
- You know.

55:01.560 --> 55:03.438
I... I think there will
be a bit of relief...

55:03.680 --> 55:04.875
- Yeah.
- That I've been able to...

55:05.720 --> 55:07.598
- Do you feel relieved now?
- A bit, yeah.

55:08.520 --> 55:09.874
(BELL RINGS)

55:11.880 --> 55:13.633
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

55:21.880 --> 55:23.109
(MAN ANNOUNCING ON PA)

55:26.240 --> 55:27.833
(INAUDIBLE)

55:36.680 --> 55:38.637
SPORTS COMMENTATOR:
<i>It's a cold winter's day here at Kempton,</i>

55:38.800 --> 55:41.110
<i>using the running rail,
coming up the stand side,</i>

55:41.200 --> 55:43.795
<i>the danger looks to be Barry Geraghty,
his great friend and rival</i>

55:43.880 --> 55:48.671
<i>on board West Wizard, but it's Minella
Rocco in the JP McManus colours,</i>

55:48.760 --> 55:51.434
<i>those distinctive colours
and now it's still out in front,</i>

55:51.520 --> 55:55.753
<i>Minella Rocco. West Wizard is the danger
as AP McCoy gets into the drive position,</i>

55:55.840 --> 56:00.278
<i>as he closes in once again, on
the magic 200. He's at 197.</i>

56:00.360 --> 56:04.400
<i>Jumping the final flight, jumps it well,
West Wizard rather dives at that</i>

56:04.480 --> 56:05.596
<i>and is left floundering.</i>

56:05.680 --> 56:08.275
<i>But it's going to be
another win for AP McCoy,</i>

56:08.360 --> 56:11.080
<i>the champ moves to 198 here in Kempton,</i>

56:11.160 --> 56:13.959
<i>with an effortless victory
here on Minella Rocco.</i>

56:14.040 --> 56:18.478
MCCOY: And basically, I'm going to retire
at the end of the season.

56:19.720 --> 56:22.713
- So, um...
- (LAUGHING)

56:24.960 --> 56:28.317
- Wow, I'm so excited.
- So...

56:29.960 --> 56:31.440
- So, it's, you know...
- CLAIRE: It's a sad thing.

56:31.520 --> 56:33.955
So, I may as well just go away and die now.

56:34.040 --> 56:35.110
CLAIRE: Oh, my goodness.

56:35.200 --> 56:37.840
You can't, look at all these
pages of things for you to do.

56:39.400 --> 56:43.030
Claire, you're... Claire's only
getting warmed up now.

56:43.200 --> 56:45.112
All the things she's being saying no to.

56:45.200 --> 56:48.238
CLAIRE: I've been waiting for this moment
for so long, however I do see, it is sad.

56:48.320 --> 56:49.913
- It is...
- MCCOY: You can just do whatever you want

56:50.000 --> 56:51.434
with my tour, I don't care.

56:52.040 --> 56:53.110
- So...
- I hate it.

56:55.800 --> 56:59.794
CLAIRE: Would you like to be the face
for peanut butter?

57:00.120 --> 57:03.750
Not the face of peanut butter,
but there's this man vs horse,

57:04.600 --> 57:07.877
I don't know it's like 40 miles or
something. They have to race against a horse

57:07.960 --> 57:10.794
and see who gets to
the finish line the quickest,

57:11.080 --> 57:13.834
however it depends on what their strategies
are, and whether it might fit in.

57:15.560 --> 57:16.960
Yeah, it's so... (CHUCKLES)

57:19.280 --> 57:21.033
- Peanut butter?
- CLAIRE: That could be quite easy.

57:21.120 --> 57:25.239
It's a day of media work. And then,
obviously, it's the face of this festival

57:25.320 --> 57:26.834
and lots of people race.

57:26.920 --> 57:29.151
So he won't be on the front
of peanut butter jar?

57:29.280 --> 57:30.634
I won't have to look at him.

57:31.040 --> 57:33.111
- Like, up in the press.
- CLAIRE: No, he's not that kid.

57:33.200 --> 57:34.600
That peanut butter kid, or whatever...

57:41.680 --> 57:43.319
That's just a possibility.

57:46.360 --> 57:50.400
MCCOY: Depressing, isn't it?
Such a depressing thought.

57:51.760 --> 57:53.353
Oh, honey.

57:56.600 --> 57:57.795
Anyway, I'm grand.

57:59.920 --> 58:00.920
Ah.

58:01.000 --> 58:02.229
You're struggling.

58:02.560 --> 58:06.759
CLAIRE: You're not bad, it was always going
to be a really hard decision

58:06.840 --> 58:09.958
and I think everyone's going to
be pretty sad when they read it.

58:10.200 --> 58:11.200
CHANELLE: Mmm.

58:12.200 --> 58:13.200
(BELL RINGS)

58:19.360 --> 58:20.840
JOCKEY ANNOUNCER: Last call, thank you.

58:45.720 --> 58:47.439
(INAUDIBLE)

58:56.240 --> 58:59.233
SPORTS COMMENTATOR: <i>Flags up.
Studs ready and are about to line up.</i>

58:59.680 --> 59:02.957
<i>Line-up's over. We're off.</i>

59:03.320 --> 59:06.631
<i>Mr Mole has just shied at the tape there.</i>

59:06.720 --> 59:10.475
<i>He was lined up in first place but he's
dropped 10 lengths behind the others.</i>

59:10.560 --> 59:13.120
<i>And gets away in last position.</i>

59:13.440 --> 59:16.274
<i>It is fat marker of the quid tip.
They take the water just once.</i>

59:16.360 --> 59:19.432
<i>It's fence number three
Uxizandre up and over safely.</i>

59:20.240 --> 59:21.594
(HOOVES THUDDING)

59:24.480 --> 59:28.474
<i>Show's in second place,
behind Sire De Grugy.</i>

59:32.920 --> 59:35.992
<i>One length of the nose bandage, Mr Mole...</i>

59:40.520 --> 59:44.070
<i>It's going to be the first of the ditchers.
Number 11 will also be an open ditch.</i>

59:46.480 --> 59:48.676
(COMMENTARY CONTINUES ON TV)

01:00:17.520 --> 01:00:22.276
<i>Into the straight. Four more fences to
jump, Uxizandre on the right leading,</i>

01:00:22.360 --> 01:00:24.875
<i>on the left with a nose bandage,
Mr Mole and between them</i>

01:00:24.960 --> 01:00:28.590
<i>the white face of Sire De Grugy,
beginning to get closer...</i>

01:00:28.920 --> 01:00:31.640
<i>Fence four from the finish there.
Mr Mole on the left,</i>

01:00:31.720 --> 01:00:35.157
<i>comes through to take it upside,
Drewson Era in third position.</i>

01:00:35.240 --> 01:00:36.720
<i>Uxizandre's in second.</i>

01:00:36.800 --> 01:00:40.032
<i>Here's the final one
of the ditches now and Mr Mole</i>

01:00:40.120 --> 01:00:42.715
<i>at the third last fence
comes in towards him,</i>

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:46.072
<i>over safely. And Sire De Grugy has
unseated Jamie Moore!</i>

01:00:46.440 --> 01:00:49.194
<i>Sire De Grugy on sixth,
Jamie Moore on the third lap.</i>

01:00:49.280 --> 01:00:50.600
<i>And Mr Mole is left clear.</i>

01:00:50.680 --> 01:00:55.516
<i>Officer Longblood has joined Uxizandre in
the second position. And the second last.</i>

01:00:55.600 --> 01:00:59.674
<i>And it's AP on Mr Mole
as he heads down towards the final fence,</i>

01:00:59.760 --> 01:01:01.194
<i>he's fifteen lengths ahead.</i>

01:01:01.280 --> 01:01:04.717
<i>Uxizandre with the riderless
Sire De Grugy next to him.</i>

01:01:04.800 --> 01:01:07.679
<i>Upsilon Bleu is next at the final obstacle.</i>

01:01:07.760 --> 01:01:10.594
<i>Mr Mole up and over the last safely.</i>

01:01:10.680 --> 01:01:16.074
<i>Uxziandre's unseated Barry Geraghty at the
last to leave Upsilon Bleu in third position.</i>

01:01:16.160 --> 01:01:17.913
<i>Good Answer in fourth.</i>

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:20.117
<i>And it's Mr Mole, messed
around at the start,</i>

01:01:20.200 --> 01:01:24.194
<i>but he will give AP McCoy
his two hundredth winner of the season.</i>

01:01:26.600 --> 01:01:29.035
<i>200 of the season for Tony McCoy,</i>

01:01:29.120 --> 01:01:32.591
<i>it's doubtful he's ridden many
more dramatic races this year.</i>

01:01:59.320 --> 01:02:00.913
INTERVIEWER:
I'm going to read off a stat here.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:06.029
I know. I hope you don't just
take it lightly but it's your tenth time

01:02:06.120 --> 01:02:08.430
that you've brought up
a double century of winners.

01:02:08.560 --> 01:02:10.552
That is quite an incredible achievement.

01:02:11.120 --> 01:02:12.713
MCCOY: I'm going to tell
you something else,

01:02:12.800 --> 01:02:14.314
it's going to be the last time
I ride 200 winners.

01:02:14.880 --> 01:02:17.679
Because, I'm going to
be retiring at the end of the season,

01:02:18.720 --> 01:02:20.439
- so there's a bit of news for you.
- INTERVIEWER: But...

01:02:20.760 --> 01:02:25.277
INTERVIEWER: That is a bit of a bombshell,
what's been the deciding factor in that, AP?

01:02:25.440 --> 01:02:28.558
MCCOY: Ah, look. It's just, um...
I want to go out at the top,

01:02:28.640 --> 01:02:32.270
I want to go out as champion jockey,
it'll be my twentieth year

01:02:32.360 --> 01:02:34.795
if I can win the Jockey's
championship and...

01:02:35.280 --> 01:02:41.151
And, I want to go out while I still enjoy
riding. And while I'm still at the top, so...

01:02:42.280 --> 01:02:45.193
My mum and dad don't even know
so they're going to find out on television.

01:02:45.320 --> 01:02:47.516
So, I think they'll be happy, to be fair.

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:50.674
Well, AP that is amazing news,

01:02:51.120 --> 01:02:54.033
just all I can say is congratulations
and well done.

01:02:56.440 --> 01:02:58.955
CHANELLE: AP's just announced he's retiring
at the end of the season.

01:03:00.520 --> 01:03:03.035
A shell-shocked winners
enclosure here at Newbury.

01:03:06.680 --> 01:03:08.956
MCCOY: Twenty's a good number
and I still enjoy it,

01:03:09.040 --> 01:03:12.590
I wanted to, hopefully, quit while I was
still riding a race or two.

01:03:13.160 --> 01:03:15.072
Because I'd really like to
go out at the top, so...

01:03:15.920 --> 01:03:17.639
Uh, look,

01:03:18.040 --> 01:03:20.191
time waits for no man
and it's not going to wait for me.

01:03:20.280 --> 01:03:23.079
- INTERVIEWER: It's quite an emotional now?
- I am, because I love riding.

01:03:23.720 --> 01:03:26.155
- You must be very happy lately.
- I am, but I don't know, it's just...

01:03:26.240 --> 01:03:29.597
It's funny because you don't
know whether you feel happy or sad,

01:03:29.680 --> 01:03:32.991
but I think it's definitely a mix of both.

01:03:37.560 --> 01:03:40.155
What are you going to do? Get a job?

01:03:41.800 --> 01:03:43.393
RICHARD: You're just milking
the PR again, aren't you?

01:03:43.720 --> 01:03:44.870
- Milking it.
- You know what?

01:03:44.960 --> 01:03:46.189
RICHARD: No pressure to keep on.

01:03:47.280 --> 01:03:48.634
Next year might, just might be your year.

01:03:48.720 --> 01:03:50.677
No pressure on you, Richard.

01:03:51.640 --> 01:03:53.518
RICHARD: Huh? I mean,
I could just finish with you.

01:03:56.080 --> 01:03:58.720
Anyway. Here's to a new life,
here's to a new husband.

01:04:01.080 --> 01:04:04.391
Here's to a husband! I can have him on
a Saturday and Sunday night.

01:04:04.480 --> 01:04:05.834
- Maybe?
- BOTH: Yeah.

01:04:05.920 --> 01:04:07.479
TV REPORTER: What's the best decision
you've ever made,

01:04:07.560 --> 01:04:09.517
with regards to your riding career?

01:04:10.680 --> 01:04:13.354
I think to become a jockey was
the best decision I ever made at all.

01:04:13.720 --> 01:04:16.474
I've got a great way of life
and I will really miss it.

01:04:17.040 --> 01:04:18.235
So I don't know what I'm going to...

01:04:18.320 --> 01:04:20.596
I'll never find anything that's
going to replace that buzz but

01:04:21.040 --> 01:04:23.475
I'm aware in sport you can't
keep going forever.

01:04:23.560 --> 01:04:24.560
Thank you.

01:04:25.080 --> 01:04:28.357
AP McCoy, quite simply a legend.

01:04:32.680 --> 01:04:35.275
CHANELLE: "On holiday in Dubai with the
family, just got back to room

01:04:35.360 --> 01:04:38.194
"and loads of texts on phone
about the husband's announcement.

01:04:38.760 --> 01:04:43.073
"I know it was going to always happen
someday, but my God, I'm still speechless,

01:04:43.600 --> 01:04:46.991
"the void left will be unfulfilled.

01:04:48.120 --> 01:04:51.875
"Love to you all
and see you soon, Graham and Becky Lee."

01:04:52.280 --> 01:04:53.634
Tch. Aw.

01:04:55.200 --> 01:04:56.200
That is sweet.

01:04:59.400 --> 01:05:02.040
MCCOY: <i>That was a lot of sadness.
I don't think it's probably the first time</i>

01:05:02.120 --> 01:05:03.315
<i>that I've probably won a race.</i>

01:05:03.680 --> 01:05:07.469
<i>Didn't really think that I'd just won or
didn't really think that I was really happy.</i>

01:05:07.960 --> 01:05:10.680
<i>You know, because of what was ahead.</i>

01:05:12.760 --> 01:05:16.993
<i>Convincing yourself to, you know,
now is the time you have to spit it out.</i>

01:05:39.440 --> 01:05:41.716
MALE VOICE ON PA: <i>Well, it's a day
we've all been looking forward to.</i>

01:05:41.800 --> 01:05:46.272
<i>The start of the festival.
The biggest event of its type in the sport,</i>

01:05:46.360 --> 01:05:49.432
<i>with four days of the most
brilliant racing in prospect.</i>

01:05:49.520 --> 01:05:52.399
<i>But there's going to be
a strange feel about this year's festival.</i>

01:05:52.480 --> 01:05:55.200
<i>Because we all... It's going to be
the last time we're going to see</i>

01:05:55.280 --> 01:05:57.272
<i>AP, the champ in action...</i>

01:05:57.360 --> 01:06:00.239
MCCOY: <i>There is nowhere,
nowhere like Cheltenham,</i>

01:06:00.440 --> 01:06:05.310
<i>and as a Jockey, you'll always be judged on
the amount of winners you rode there.</i>

01:06:05.400 --> 01:06:07.756
SPORTS INTERVIEWER: <i>There's been
so much written, Tony, about this week</i>

01:06:07.840 --> 01:06:10.753
and you in particular because
it will be your final festival.

01:06:10.840 --> 01:06:13.958
Has that in anyway affected your
preparations or thinking?

01:06:14.520 --> 01:06:16.751
Um, not really to be
honest, I'm quite lucky,

01:06:16.840 --> 01:06:21.073
<i>that whenever I get out on a horse,
then I'm pretty much on my own anyway.</i>

01:06:21.160 --> 01:06:25.154
<i>So I'm quite good at blanking it all out.
It'll be a little different this year</i>

